        // Austria National Day translations
        austria_national_day_title: 'üá¶üáπ October 26 ‚Äî Austria National Day',
        austria_national_day_description: 'Today Austria celebrates one of its most important national holidays ‚Äî National Day.\n\nüìñ A bit of history:\nAfter the end of World War II, Austria was under occupation by the Allied powers (USSR, USA, Great Britain and France). Only in 1955 was the State Treaty signed, which restored the country\'s independence.\n\nHowever, one of the key conditions was Austria\'s obligation to maintain permanent neutrality. On October 26, 1955, parliament passed a law establishing this status. Since then, Austria has not joined military blocs and does not host foreign military bases on its territory.\n\nüéâ Why this day is important:\n\n‚Ä¢ Symbol of the country\'s independence and freedom.\n‚Ä¢ Reminder of the value of peace and neutrality.\n‚Ä¢ Day when military parades, cultural events, and tours of government institutions take place throughout Austria.\n\nüí° Interesting fact: although the treaty itself was signed in May 1955, it was October 26 that became the national holiday ‚Äî after all, that\'s when Austria officially declared to the world: "We are a neutral country."',
