        ukrainian_language_title: 'Why Russians don\'t understand Ukrainian ‚Äî briefly',
        ukrainian_language_asymmetric: 'Asymmetric understanding: Ukrainians understand Russian not because of "language proximity", but due to years of Russification, education, and media. Russians, however, have not learned or heard Ukrainian on a mass scale.',
        ukrainian_language_lexical: 'Lexical difference:\n\nukr + Belarusian ‚Äî ~84% shared vocabulary\nukr + Polish ‚Äî ~70%\nukr + Russian ‚Äî only ~62%\n‚Üí Ukrainian is closer to West Slavic languages than to Russian.',
        ukrainian_language_origin: 'Different language origins:\n\nUkrainian ‚Äî continuous development of the living language of Rus\';\nRussian ‚Äî formed under strong influence of Church Slavonic, Finno-Ugric, and Turkic languages.',
        ukrainian_language_barriers: 'Grammatical and phonetic barriers: vocative case, different phonetics, different sound alternations ‚Äî all of this complicates Russians\' auditory perception of Ukrainian.',
        ukrainian_language_psychological: 'Psychological factor: imperial propaganda has denigrated the Ukrainian language for decades, creating unwillingness to perceive and learn it.',
        ukrainian_language_conclusion: 'Main conclusion: Ukrainian is not a dialect or a "branch", but an independent, full-fledged language with its own development path. Misunderstanding is a consequence of colonial policy, not the "strangeness" of the language.',
